./.title: Team Bob the Developer
./.body:
Team
I've written this document in order to set the standards and expectations of Team Bob the Developer. This document contains information ranging from writing guidelines to strategic partnership.
The Mission
I pursue learning as a way to provide great product and service for the community. As a whole, we work towards building an universal platform where people can learn and contribute in exchange for personal and financial incentives.
Current Focus

Provide an online blogging platform: create a web app and server.
Produce content: write and publish weekly blog articles.
Recruit: find great talents for content generation and translation.

content/team/culture.html.title: Culture
content/team/culture.html.body:
Culture
It is not the easiest job to manage a group of individuals at different time zones. Most of us have a have full-time job. It is important to maintain a few protocols to keep each other accountable so that we may step forward one at a time.
1. Driven by deadlines: When we work remotely, it is imperative that we set the expectation clear. On a weekly basis, we schedule for the next meeting along with the tasks to be completed. We catch up via Google Hangout.
2. Experience does not matter, content does: You are encouraged to write on a topic that you've begun learning as long as you do your research and make the content phenomenal. I've started my blogging journey without knowing about the materials. I studied and figured them out. As you've heard, teaching is the best way not only to learn, but also to retain the most. However, it is conditioned that you've researched more than anyone else in the chosen topic.
3. Pursue quality over quantity: We live in a noisy world include notifications, emails, and so on. You are encouraged to go deep. When you aim for quality, metrics in forms of comments, shares, and recommendations, will speak for themselves.

content/blog/styling-guide.html.title: Styling Guide
content/blog/styling-guide.html.body:
Markdown
The platform will automatically parse the markdown you've uploaded. Therefore, it is important to maintain the style for consistent user experience.
Heading

# for the  title
## for the subtitle
### and #### for the rest of headings and sub-headings

Image
Every image should have description by using the markdown syntax
![Image description](/path/to/image)
Inline Comment
Try to minimize the usage of inline comment. Instead, try to explain what's happening using a normal paragraph. The code area should be only used for code when it comes to writing tutorials. The below isn't recommended.
Not Preferred
do { // Let's try to run the function block.
 try autoDriveTesla()
} // the autoDriveTeslas block is only executed within do-try

If you need to explain multiple spots, feel free to use numbers instead.
Preferred
do { // 1
 try autoDriveTesla()  // 2
 } catch TeslaError.lostGPS {
  print("Bruh, I'm lost. Hold me tight")  // 3
 } catch TeslaError.lowBattery {
  print("HURRY! üíÄ")
 }
}

When you describe, now you may refer to the spot using the assigned number above. Again, it doesn't mean you can't use in-line comments, but excessive comments should be avoided. 
Writing Tools

In-browser markdown editor - StackEdit
Example markdown of Intro to Error Handling - intro-error-handling.md
Spelling and grammar check - Grammarly

content/blog/writing-guide.html.title: Writing Guide
content/blog/writing-guide.html.body:
Writing Guideline
If you are new to content producing, that's great. It could be daunting to first try. This is my personal guideline. It is my style, but it seems like it has been working at least for me.

Share your experience: The best way to write is to write as if you were telling a story to your younger self when you first encountered the topic. The way you tell your story is different for all individuals.

Use emojis only if you want to get your meaning across: Articles filled with an excessive number of emojis possibly give an impression of lack of credibility and being needy for attention. Again, the majority of readers is consisted of 25-30 year-old white males.

Begin with why: It is mostly good to begin with why you've decided to write the particular topic to increase the reader's interest. For example, before I introduce a concept ingenerics, I'd write about my past. You can find one example here

Show vulnerability if any: It is okay to the reader that you are new to the topic.  The truth whether you are experienced in that topic does not matter as much as your ability to distribute great content. Again, most people are here to learn from you.

Show credentials if any: You do not need to have this when you write a blog because the number of recommendations and hearts will speak for themselves. But, it is okay an good idea to tell people why people care what you have to say. If there isn't, again, feel free to show your vulnerability.

Drawings speak for themselves: I love visualizations, so do most readers. Try to create a simple diagram. The diagram, however, has to look simple but concise. The below is an example. If you need any help, I can help you draw one.

content/blog/translation-guide.html.title: Translation Guide
content/blog/translation-guide.html.body:
Blog Translation Guideline

The translator is the author of the content: He/she may use "I"s. The translator has the ownership of the content. The original version should be considered as the template only. If there is 'Bob' in the title, please feel free to change it to your name.
Feel free to add your own comment and thought: Feel free to add your own comment to sound like a non-google translate. In other words, you can add your own email and social media.
The language within code snippets should be localized: If there is any source code, it should be attached to the translator's git repository for personal branding and localization. If you need any help with localizing diagrams, I will render new drawings.

Example
The below is an example of a Spanish version. Notice that every word has bee localized for familiarity besides the swift syntax. This is something Google Translate isn't capable of doing at least for now since it would also translate the Swift syntax.
